The table shown is partially filled in with the results of a survey done by the radio station KMAT. How many of the females surveyed listen to this station?

\begin{tabular}{| l | c | r |}
\hline
& listen & don't listen \\
\hline
males & 62 & \\ \hline
females & & 102 \\ \hline
total & 130 & 150 \\
\hline
\end{tabular}
inference:
1. Total who listen = 130
2. Total who don't listen = 150
3. Total surveyed = Total who listen + Total who don't listen = 130 + 150 = 280
4. Males who listen = 62
5. Males who don't listen = Total males - Males who listen = (280 - 130) - 62 = 150 - 62 = 88
6. Females who don't listen = 102
7. Females who listen = Total females - Females who don't listen = 280 - 150 - 102 = 28
8. Total who listen = 130 = Males who listen + Females who listen = 62 + Females who listen 
9. Females who listen = 130 - 62 = 68

Final Answer: $\boxed{68}$
ground_truth: Since there were a total of $130$ people surveyed who listen to this station and we know that $62$ of them are male, $130-62=\boxed{68}$ of the females surveyed said that they listen to this station.
